<pb facs="hta.008.001"/>
    
    <head>LECTURE IV.</head>
    <head type="sub">GENESIS, VII. PART OF VER. 13. <lb/>
        <hi rend="italic">And Noah only remained alive, and they that were with him in the ark.</hi></head>

    <p>To such a degree of wickedness of were mankind arrived in the course of ten generations, that the historian seems almost at a loss for expressions of sufficient force. He tells us that God saw that the wickedness of man was great in the earth : we must understand herby, that its enormity was become audacious, and thrust itself into the notice of God, so that the honour of his name rendered farther forbearance impossible. That God always does see every individual crime committed on the earth, is undeniable; not only committed crimes, but the seeds of every evil action whilst yet it is lurking in the heart. But it should seem that the overflowings of his wrath are reserved until all hopes of amendment are removed by the extent as well as depth of iniquity. Such overflowings, therefore, of divine wrath (which, after all, is but divine justice), as they can never be in the
        
<pb facs="hta.008.002"/>
        
    least foreseen or calculated upon by us, so ought they always to be considered as most likely to be poured out, when whole nations are sunk in debauchery, or totally wrapt up in vain, worldly, and proud pursuits; when they adopt and avow publicly false systems of religion; when they set at nought the only proffered mode of salvation, because they cannot demonstrate all the means which it employs; when they neglect public worship and private prayers; when they disregard God's sacraments, which are the voice whereby he now speaks to mankind; when they cease to search the Scriptures, and either leave their salvation to chance, or claim it as the reward due unto them, for conducting themselves in general according to the precepts of a decent morality, and hiding their favorite sin from public inspection. It is more than probable, that many nations may have thrust themselves, as it were, upon the edge of God's mercy, and may be really most obnoxious to his wrath, when they apepar to be enjoying his favour, on account of their external prosperity. We may be wisely reminded by the testimony of Holy Writ, that when God looked down with closer aspect on the crimes of the antediluvian sinners, he did not, at the time, give them any particular warning. They evinced neither knowledge nor apprehension of their impending destruction. This is no matter of conjecture; our Saviour
    
<pb facs="hta.008.003"/>    
    
    describes their supineness, by likening unto it the deplorable thoughtlessness and besotted security of those who were to be overwhlemed in the destruction of Jerusalem, and those who shall fall into the hands of the living God at the last day. (St. Mark, xxiv. 38.) "As the days of Noah were, so shall also the coming of the Son of Man be. For as, in the days that were before the flood, they were eating and drinking, marrying and giving in marriage, until the day that Noe entered into the ark, and knew not until the flood came and took them all away; so also shall the coming of the Son of Man be." Here we cannot but observe, that our Saviour, desirous of representing as strongly as possible the suddenness with which Jerusalem should be destroyed, and the probable greater suddenness with which this earth shall be dissolved in an hour which no man knoweth of, can compare it only to the instantaneous operation of the deluge. "They know not until the flood came and took them all away."&#8212;Alas! how frequently is this exemplified even to this day in the fate of individuals! They flatter themselves that they are so strong that they cannot be moved; or they count upon warnings, which have been already lavished upon them; or they say, "Tush, God will not perceive it, the Most High regardeth it not;" till their visitation cometh with the silence of a thief in the night, and the
    
<pb facs="hta.008.004"/>   
    
    </p>



